<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF76FCE7FC7DFC9A" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" box="[151,925,865,892]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Size. Known adult size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F09FF9EFE07FCE7FDB8FC9D" box="[486,600,865,892]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="cm" value="17.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="15.0">15–20 cm</quantity>
, reaching 
<quantity id="2E379B383F09FF9EFD2BFCE7FCEFFC9D" box="[714,783,865,892]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="cm" value="25.0">25 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F09FF9EFF26FC03FC8DF956" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26FC03FB0CFBB5" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Morphology. D V–VII + I,13–16; A I,12–16; P 17–20. Body stout and distinctly compressed laterally (for a 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F09FF9EFF4FFC2FFEBEFC25" box="[174,350,937,964]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFF4FFC2FFF1FFC22" box="[174,255,937,963]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Gobius</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
), especially on caudal peduncle. Proportionally small eyes. Snout moderately long and with a moderately steep profile. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. The first dorsal fin about equal to, or shorter than the second dorsal fin, with more or less rounded distal edge. Dorsal-fin ray tips become free from membrane in reproductive males (Toricelli 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFD6CFB90FD22FBCE" box="[653,706,1045,1071]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 2000). Caudal fin rounded. Scales small, visible on body and usually also on predorsal area as pattern of pale dots. Predorsal area and nape scaled (Miller 1986).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26FBDBFEFFFA5A" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Live coloration. Body coloration gray-green to pale fawn dorsally, whitish to yellow-green ventrally (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F09FF9EFADAFBDBFA70FB96" box="[1339,1424,1117,1143]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1055,1079]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 44. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius ophiocephalus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Russia, Black Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601709" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601709/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFF76FB07FA7CFB02" bold="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Eight to fourteen irregular, vertical dark bars along the lateral midline, forming dark lateral zigzag markings in combination with a series of 10 or more dark areas alternating with pale interspaces on lower side. A diffuse, light to golden dorsolateral stripe runs from predorsal area to caudal-fin base, not always visible</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F09FF9EFF41FB6BFF15FAE6" box="[160,245,1261,1287]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1055,1079]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 44. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius ophiocephalus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Russia, Black Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601709" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601709/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). It is bordered ventrally by an olive-brown stripe, and dorsally by a dark vertebral stripe. In the Adriatic, these stripes can be interrupted by dark transverse saddles. One oblique dark preorbital bar, bordered ventrally by a white suborbital bar. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFE61FAB3FF06FA92" bold="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Cheek and preopercle mottled brown-olive with white spots of various sizes and irregular shapes</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F09FF9EFF17FADFFEABFA92" box="[246,331,1369,1395]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1055,1079]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[156,1431,181,1031]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 44. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius ophiocephalus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Russia, Black Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601709" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601709/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). First dorsal fin reddish with 4 gray-blue transverse bands. Second dorsal fin with the same color but with gray-blue irregular markings not forming clearly defined bands, and with many small white dots (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F09FF9EFAA3FAFBFEF3FA5A" author="Renoult, J. P. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P." pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref63723" refString="Renoult, J. P., Pillon, R., Kovacic, M. &amp; Louisy, P. (2022) Frontiers in Fishwatching Series - Gobies of North-eastern Atlantic and the Mediterranean: Gobius and Thorogobius. Les cahiers de la fondation Biotope. [in press]" type="book" year="2022">
Renoult 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFF76FA24FF28FA5A" box="[151,200,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26FA43FDC9FA01" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" box="[199,553,1477,1504]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F09FF9EFE9EFA43FDC2FA3E" authorityName="Pallas" authorityYear="1814" box="[383,546,1477,1503]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cobitis">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFE9EFA43FDC2FA3E" box="[383,546,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Gobius cobitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26FA6FFCFCF9C6" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Habitat. Known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F09FF9EFE21FA6FFDFCF9E5" box="[448,540,1513,1540]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="m" value="1.55" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="0.1">0.1–3 m</quantity>
depth, eurythermal and euryhyaline, on soft bottoms with marine phanerogams in estuaries and coastal lagoons (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F09FF9EFDE6F98BFCF1F9C6" author="Kara, M. H. &amp; Quignard, J. P." box="[519,785,1549,1575]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref57109" refString="Kara, M. H. &amp; Quignard, J. P. (2019) Fishes in Lagoons and Estuaries in the Mediterranean. Vol. 2. Sedentary Fish. John Wiley &amp; Son, New York, New York, 441 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / 9781119452768" type="book" year="2019">Kara &amp; Quignard 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26F9B7FCA9F98E" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean, Adriatic, Black Sea and Sea of Azov. Along the African coasts, confirmed records from 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F09FF9EFE49F9D3FE09F98E" box="[424,489,1621,1647]" name="Libya" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Libya</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F09FF9EFDFEF9D3FD92F98E" box="[543,626,1621,1647]" name="Tunisia" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F09FF9EFD61F9D3FCDEF98E" author="Hajji, F. &amp; Ouannes-Ghorbel, A. &amp; Ghorbe, M. &amp; Jarboui, O." box="[640,830,1621,1648]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="27 - 39" refId="ref55902" refString="Hajji, F., Ouannes-Ghorbel, A., Ghorbe, M. &amp; Jarboui, O. (2013) Age and growth of the grass goby Zosterisessor ophiocephalus Pallas, 1811 in the Gulf of Gabes (Tunisia, Central Mediterranean). Acta Adriatica, 54, 27 - 39." type="journal article" year="2013">
Hajji 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFD23F9D0FD13F98E" box="[706,755,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F09FF9EFF26F9FFFC8DF956" blockId="60.[151,1437,865,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Remark. Often classified in its own genus 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F09FF9EFD7CF9FCFC39F975" authority="Whitley, 1935" authorityName="Whitley" authorityYear="1935" box="[669,985,1657,1684]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zosterisessor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFD7CF9FCFCD2F972" box="[669,818,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Zosterisessor</emphasis>
Whitley, 1935
</taxonomicName>
, but its position within the genus 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F09FF9EFAAAF9FFFA7CF972" authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1355,1436,1657,1683]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFAAAF9FFFA7CF972" box="[1355,1436,1657,1683]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Gobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confirmed by a phylogenetic analysis (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F09FF9EFD9AF91BFC81F956" author="Iglesias, S. P. &amp; Vukic, J. &amp; Sellos, D. Y. &amp; Soukupova, T. &amp; Sanda, R." box="[635,865,1693,1720]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="445 - 449" refId="ref56737" refString="Iglesias, S. P., Vukic, J., Sellos, D. Y., Soukupova, T. &amp; Sanda, R. (2021 a) Gobius xoriguer, a new offshore Mediterranean goby (Gobiidae), and phylogenetic relationships within the genus Gobius. Ichthyological Research, 68 (3), 445 - 449. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10228 - 020 - 00797 - 9" type="journal article" year="2021">
Iglésias 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F09FF9EFD38F918FCEAF956" box="[729,778,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al</emphasis>
. 2021a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
